(170754, '96A9832E-0518-4A30-8769-9A1B577AE780', 'I know the apology was right, but if I had thought it would have put Nathan in that position, I wouldn''t have done it. I know you think in certain instances I''m over protective, but this isn''t one. It is too much of a burden for a (sensitive) 12 year old and it caused him real difficulties last year. But it will offer an opportunity for me to talk to him about it and discuss forgiveness (and fallibility).  Read this book during our couples therapy called Forgive for Good, which had a really useful methodology for dealing with this. One of the insights I had was how withholding forgiveness was holding me back, and how my anger/feelings of being wronged (and the way I then acted) just were crutches for my ego. It took up emotional real estate that I wanted to use  for something better. With that, i could let go...although it still is a process.  As far as my mom, I agree but for different reasons...it is bad for her. Marla uses her as an emotional crutch and the whole thing just depresses my mom, who doesn''t know how to deal with everything going on with me and my sister and ultimately my brother. This is a different conversation though.  I need to work on the ''better dad''''category of goals...been thinking about it. ', '464646586000000000', '464648797000000000', 1, 'David', 'Nitzan', 0, '', '', '', 'iMessage', 'None', 'David', '2015-09-22T13:29:46'),
